    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That feels a little bit like I'm just telling my students one side is right and the other is just driven by fear. If I want to be fair to the legal arguments, shouldn't I also explain the procedural side of due process? Is there a significant difference in how they actually function in a courtroom?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The procedural due process clause is fundamentally different because it focuses strictly on *how* the government acts, not *what* it acts upon. Procedural due process demands fair processes—like proper notice and a chance to be heard—before the government can deprive someone of life, liberty, or property. While substantive due process looks at the *substance* of the law to protect rights, procedural due process ensures the *fairness* of the legal mechanism itself.",
      "source": "target",
